│ `Assertion '(BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width || BestPlan.hasEarlyExit() || planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(getPlanFor(BestFactor.Width), CostCtx, OrigLoop) ||                  │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(getPlanFor(LegacyVF.Width), CostCtx, OrigLoop)) && " VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed"' failed.`                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ This assertion indicates a disagreement between the new VPlan cost model and the old legacy cost model for loop vectorization. The reproducer involves a first-order recurrence that is  │
│ a candidate for scalarization. The assertion suggests that for some vectorization factor (VF), one model thinks it's better while the other doesn't, and the tie-breaking logic doesn't  │
│ cover this specific case.                                                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The backtrace points to `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp:7667`.                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The core of the issue is that the VPlan cost model and the legacy cost model can come to different conclusions about the optimal vectorization factor (VF). The assertion is in place to │
│ catch unexpected discrepancies. The allowed discrepancies are when the VFs are equal, when the VPlan has an early exit (which the legacy model doesn't reason about), or when a plan     │
│ involves "additional simplifications" not modeled by the legacy coster.                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The reproducer's loop contains a first-order recurrence: `%for = phi i32 [ 4, %entry ], [ %iv, %loop ]`. This recurrence can be "scalarized" during vectorization, meaning it's handled  │
│ with scalar instructions within the vectorized loop body. This scalarization is one of the "additional simplifications".                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The problem arises because the decision to scalarize a recurrence can depend on the chosen vectorization factor. For a given VF, if scalarization is deemed profitable, the cost of the  │
│ loop changes. It seems that for the failing test case, the VPlan model and the legacy model disagree on the best VF, and this disagreement stems from how they evaluate the              │
│ profitability of scalarizing the recurrence at different VFs.                                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The assertion includes `planContainsAdditionalSimplifications` to account for this. However, it seems this check is not sufficient. A common pattern for fixing such assertions is to    │
│ expand the conditions under which a disagreement is considered acceptable.                                                                                                               │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Looking at the surrounding code and similar fixes, a likely cause is that the check for simplifications is too restrictive. The assertion checks if either the VPlan-chosen best plan or │
│ the legacy-chosen best plan have additional simplifications. However, it's possible that *any* of the considered plans for *any* VF have simplifications, and this affects the cost      │
│ model in a way that leads to the final disagreement on the best VF.                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ A reasonable fix is to broaden the condition in the assertion. Instead of only checking the plans for the two chosen VFs (`BestFactor.Width` and `LegacyVF.Width`), we should check if   │
│ *any* of the generated plans for *any* of the considered VFs contain these additional simplifications. If so, we acknowledge that the cost models are operating on different assumptions │
│ and permit a mismatch in the final chosen VF.                                                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ To implement this, I will introduce a boolean flag, `AnyPlanHasAdditionalSimplifications`, which will be set to true if any plan generated for any considered VF has additional          │
│ simplifications. Then, I will add this flag to the assertion condition.                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The change will be in `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF()` in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`.                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ 1.  Initialize `bool AnyPlanHasAdditionalSimplifications = false;` before iterating through possible VFs.                                                                                │
│ 2.  Inside the loop that builds plans for each VF, update the flag: `AnyPlanHasAdditionalSimplifications |= planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(Plan, CostCtx, OrigLoop);`.            │
│ 3.  Modify the assertion to include this new flag: `... || AnyPlanHasAdditionalSimplifications)`.                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ This approach acknowledges that the very presence of certain optimization opportunities (like recurrence scalarization) can lead to legitimate disagreements between the two cost        │
│ models, and thus the assertion should be relaxed in such cases.                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
